Creating a smooth and visually appealing version of the classic Snake game in C using images for graphics can be a challenging but rewarding project. To achieve smooth animation, you will need to use a graphics library that allows you to render images and handle input efficiently. One common library used for such purposes in C is Simple DirectMedia Layer (SDL). Below are the steps and a high-level overview of how to create the Snake game using SDL in C.

1. **Install SDL**: Before you begin coding, you'll need to make sure you have SDL installed on your system. SDL provides the necessary functions for rendering images and handling user input. You can download SDL from its official website (https://www.libsdl.org/) and follow the installation instructions for your platform.

2. **Set up your project**: Create a new project and configure it to link against the SDL library. You'll need to include SDL headers in your C files and link against SDL2 during compilation.

3. **Initialize SDL**: At the beginning of your `main` function, initialize SDL and create a window and a renderer.

4. **Load images**: Load the images you'll use for the snake, food, and level background. Ensure these images are optimized for smooth rendering.

5. **Game loop**: Implement the game loop, where you'll handle events (like keyboard input), update the game state, and render the images.

6. **Snake mechanics**: Create the data structures and logic necessary to handle the snake's movement and growth.

7. **Collision detection**: Implement collision detection to check for the snake colliding with itself, the walls, or the food.

8. **Score and levels**: Keep track of the player's score and implement levels or increasing difficulty as the game progresses.

9. **Cleanup**: When the game ends, be sure to free any loaded resources and shut down SDL properly.

Here's a very simplified version of what the main parts of your code might look like, assuming you have already set up SDL and loaded your images:

```c
#include <SDL.h>

// Define your screen dimensions and other constants
const int SCREEN_WIDTH = 640;
const int SCREEN_HEIGHT = 480;

int main(int argc, char* args[]) {
    SDL_Window* window = NULL;
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = NULL;
    SDL_Texture* snakeTexture = NULL; // Your snake image
    SDL_Texture* foodTexture = NULL; // Your food image
    SDL_Texture* backgroundTexture = NULL; // Your background image

    // Initialize SDL
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) < 0) {
        // Handle error
        return -1;
    }

    // Create window
    window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_UNDEFINED, SCREEN_WIDTH, SCREEN_HEIGHT, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    if (!window) {
        // Handle error
        SDL_Quit();
        return -1;
    }

    // Create renderer
    renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (!renderer) {
        // Handle error
        SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
        SDL_Quit();
        return -1;
    }

    // Load images as textures
    snakeTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "path_to_snake_image.png");
    foodTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "path_to_food_image.png");
    backgroundTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "path_to_background_image.png");

    // Check if textures are loaded
    if (!snakeTexture || !foodTexture || !backgroundTexture) {
        // Handle error
        // Destroy textures, renderer, and window
        // Quit SDL
        return -1;
    }

    // Game loop flag
    bool quit = false;

    // Event handler
    SDL_Event e;

    // While application is running
    while (!quit) {
        // Handle events on queue
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&e) != 0) {
            // User requests quit
            if (e.type == SDL_QUIT) {
                quit = true;
            }
            // Handle other events like keyboard input
        }

        // Clear screen
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

        // Render background texture to screen
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, backgroundTexture, NULL, NULL);

        // Render snake texture to screen
        // You'll need to update the position based on the game logic
        SDL_Rect snakePosition = { /* ... */ };
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeTexture, NULL, &snakePosition);

        // Render food texture to screen
        SDL_Rect foodPosition = { /* ... */ };
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, foodTexture, NULL, &foodPosition);

        // Update screen
        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);

        // Delay to cap frame rate
        SDL_Delay(16); // Approximately 60 frames per second
    }

    // Free resources and close SDL
    SDL_DestroyTexture(snakeTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(foodTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(backgroundTexture);
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();

    return 0;
