 Additionally, how can you create different colors for each row of the chessboard? Here is a sample FEN notation: 
##
8/8/4k3/3pP2p/2BP4/2PPP3/8/8 w - - 0 1
To draw a chessboard based on the given FEN notation, we need to first understand what the notation means:

- The notation represents a chessboard with 64 squares arranged in an 8x8 grid.
- Each square has a unique identifier (ranks) from 1 to 8, starting from one end of the board (white side).
- Each row (file) of the board has alternating colored squares, starting with a light-colored square at the far right end of the board (white side).
- The notation also includes information about the position of the pieces on the board.

Now, let's create a LATEX code to draw the chessboard using the `tikz` package:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[draw=black,thick]

% draw the chessboard grid
\foreach \i in {1,...,8} {
  \foreach \j in {1,...,8} {
    \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\color}{mod(\i+\j,2)}
    \pgfmathsetmacro{\shade}{ifthenelse(\color==0,"gray","white")}
    \fill[\shade] (\j,\i) rectangle ++(1cm,1cm);
  }
}

% add piece positions (example)
\node[minimum size=1.5em,fill=red!50] at (4.5,4.5) {};
\node[minimum size=1.5em,fill=blue!50] at (5.5,5.5) {};

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

In this code, we use nested `foreach` loops to iterate through each cell of the board and draw it with the appropriate color. We calculate the color by adding the rank and file numbers together and checking if the sum is even or odd. If it's even, we shade the square gray; if it's odd, we shade it white. We also include some code to add piece positions as examples (in this case, a red piece at (4.5,4.5) and a blue piece at (5.5,5.5)).

To apply different colors to each row of the chessboard, we can modify the shading command within the loop to use a predefined list of colors. For example, we can use a list of shades of gray or a list of pastel colors:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[draw=black,thick]

% define a list of colors to use for the rows
\def\rowcolors{gray!20,gray!40,gray!60,gray!80,white,white,white,white}

% draw the chessboard grid with alternating row colors
\foreach \i in {1,...,8} {
  \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\shade}{\rowcolors[\i mod 8]}
  \foreach \j in {1,...,8} {
    \fill[\shade] (\j,\i) rectangle ++(1cm,1cm);
  }
}

% add piece positions (example)
\node[minimum size=1.5em,fill=red!50] at (4.5,4.5) {};
\node[minimum size=1.5em,fill=blue!50] at (5.5,5.5) {};

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

In this modified code, we define a list of colors called `\rowcolors`, which contains eight shades of gray and four white shades. We then use the `\shade` variable in the `\fill` command to apply the correct color to each row based on its index in the list. Note that we use the modulo operator (`\i mod 8`) to wrap around to the beginning of the list when we reach the end. With this modification, each row of the chessboard will have a different color based on its position in the list.<|im_end|>

